<div id="comment_64979741" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64979741" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64979741" name="comment_link_64979741" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23535965&amp;cid=64979741" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64979741)" >Cable vs Satellite</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64979741" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64979741); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Roger+W+Moore">Roger W Moore</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~Roger+W+Moore">( 538166 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64979741"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64979741"><p><div class="quote"><p>Satellite to satellite communications are faster<nobr> <wbr></nobr>...and higher bandwidth than any fiber optic cable.</p></div><p>
Speed-wise yes, latency-wise unlikely because the distance is further you have hundred to a thousand or two of extra kilometres to and from orbit depending on the location of the satellite plus added distance bouncing between satellites whose positions shift as they orbit. Also satellite bandwidth is tiny compared to undersea cables. Also the estimates I have seen for the full-size V2 starlink satellites is around 100Gbps per satellite compared to ~10+ Tbps for modern undersea cables.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64979741">

</div>
